column1: Data Supplied By: National Livestock Reporting Service
Data source: National Livestock Reporting Service
Please see terms of use here: https://www.mla.com.au/general/Terms-and-conditions/data-and-information/

There was a greater volume of supplies today.  Good runs of mostly well-bred local  weaners, yearlings and grown cattle were presented as well as pastoral stocks covering all categoryâ€™s from well weighted grown steers and heifers and big lines of pastoral bulls down to clean up store calves of all sexs. Values remain similar with most regulars present in the buyer gallery and Live export active on Pastoral steers and bulls.

The majority of weaner steers sold from 300c to 352c to average 343c and the best weaner heifers from 200c to 294c/kg.   Lighter yearling steers in store and feedlot condition made 220c to 320c and with more weight up to 366c/kg. Plain yearling heifers ranged from 168c to 234c and with bigger frame and cover from 242c to 276c/kg.

Pastoral lightweight steer calves started from 168c up to 250c with bigger frame and cover.  Heavier pastoral heifer calves were making 192c to 244c however plainer heifers lacking frame size and weight were again difficult to offload ranging 60c to 160c/kg.

Grown steers returned 220c to 300c while most grown heifers sold from 200c up to 308c/kg.  Store and feeder cows ranged from 82c to 170c while medium cows returned 184c to 206c and prime cows realized 222c/kg.

Shipping bulls ranged from 180c to 276c and local slaughter bulls lifted slightly to return 180c to 214c/kg.
Terry Birkin NLIS.
